{"query": "When restoring grasslands, how do the outcomes of simply disturbing the soil before seeding compare to removing the topsoil entirely?", "summary": "Based on studies examining grassland restoration techniques, removing topsoil/turf before seeding generally produces better outcomes compared to simply disturbing the soil. One replicated, randomized, paired, controlled study in the UK found that removing turf before sowing seeds increased grass species richness in most cases compared to disturbing the soil before sowing (action 3415). The same study found that removing turf before sowing seeds increased forb species richness in most cases compared to disturbing the soil before sowing (action 3415). 

Studies on removing topsoil or turf showed additional benefits including: increased plant community similarity to intact steppe habitat (action 3415), increased plant species richness (action 3415), increased species richness of sown plants (action 3415), higher cover of planted species (action 3415), and increased survival of seedlings and plants in two studies (action 3415).

For soil disturbance alone, studies showed more mixed results: one of two studies found that disturbing soil before sowing seeds increased plant and seedling species richness while the other found no change in plant species richness or diversity (action 3413). Four of five studies found that disturbing soil before sowing seeds increased plant emergence in most cases compared to sowing alone, while one study found no change in seed germination (action 3413). One of two studies found that disturbing soil increased seedling survival while the other found no effect on survival of planted species (action 3413).", "action_ids": ["3415","3413"]}

